Here is an example of how you can create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that uses slash commands and has a single command, `ban`:

```javascript
const Discord = require("discord.js");
const { Client, Intents } = require("discord.js");

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES] });
client.commands = new Discord.Collection();
client.slashCommands = new Discord.Collection();

client.on("ready", () => {
  console.log("Ready!");
});

client.on("interactionCreate", async interaction => {
  const commandId = interaction.commandName;
  const command = client.commands.get(commandId) || client.slashCommands.get(commandId);
  if (!command) return;
  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
});
```
This code defines a client object with a collection of commands and a collection of slash commands. It also sets up an event listener for interactionCreate events, which fires when a user interacts with a command or slash command using the / prefix (slash commands use the / prefix). The event listener then searches the command and slash command collections for the command that was used, and if found, calls the execute method on the command object to execute the command's logic. If the command was not found, the event listener returns without doing anything else.

